, Maghbouleh documents Iranian Americans' shifting racial status. Drawing on never-before-analyzed historical and legal evidence, she captures the unique experience of an immigrant group trapped between legal racial invisibility and everyday racial hyper-visibility. Her findings are essential for understanding the unprecedented challenge Middle Easterners now face under "extreme vetting" and potential reclassification out of the "white" box. Maghbouleh tells for the first time the compelling, often heartbreaking story of how a white American immigrant group can become brown and what such a transformation says about race in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aIranian AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aIranian AmericansxRace identity. 0aIranian AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aRacismzUnited States. 4aAssimilation. 4aImmigration. 4aIranian-Americans. 4aMiddle Easterners. 4aRace. 4aRacialization. 4aWhiteness. 4aYouth. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360343140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603431423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603431.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles